snippet.textDisplay:
My grandma is the one who got me into Nintendo. I had already played a bit of Mario and stuff at other kids’ houses, but I had a Sega Genesis at home and was a big Sonic boi.

When I was 9, my brother and I moved in with my grandma, who was albino and legally blind, btw. She was retired, and one way she kept herself busy was playing NES and SNES (she had a big screen TV and could see well enough to play games). She introduced us to Zelda, Metroid, and a whole bunch of other classics. When me and my brother would get stuck on a challenging boss or puzzle, she would be the one to help us figure it out.

To this day, the games I played at her house are my all time favorites, and playing those games with her are some of my best memories, period.

I think people underestimate how positive video games can potentially be for the elderly and retired, especially Nintendo games due to their relative simplicity. If you love games and have someone like this in your life, I highly recommend trying to share your hobby with them. I wish I still could.

RIP, gramma. Leave luck to heaven...
